Introduction

Retailers like Walmart often struggle with setting optimal product prices that balance competitiveness and profitability. Incorrect pricing can lead to either reduced sales or diminished margins

Business overview On the other hand, a price automation solution with Machine Learning implies training a model capable of automatically price items the way they would be priced by a human expert at scale. The model could take in historical data and different characteristics of the product as well as unstructured data such as images and text and would learn the pricing rules with no explicit coding, adapting to changes in the environment in a much richer and dynamic way.

Research questions -

  1. Product Trend Analysis Identify popular products, analyze seasonal trends, and gain insights into consumer demand to refine your marketing and inventory strategies.

  2. Which cutomer segments are profitable?

  3. Which customers are at the risk of churning

  4. Consumer Sentiment Analysis Analyze reviews, ratings, and feedback to understand customer sentiment toward specific products or categories and improve your offerings.

Metholodology -

  1. Use historic sales data, pricing history, product information, store location, weather and holiday information
  2. Create lag features, rolling means, price elasticity
  3. Use ML models to predict sales volumes and optimize prices

Rferences -

https://tryolabs.com/blog/price-optimization-machine-learning

Dataset overview - Some of the data points include: title: Product title description: A brief description of the product initial_price: Initial price of the product final_price: Current or discounted price currency: Currency in which the product is priced availability: Product availability status (e.g., in stock or out of stock) reviews_count: Number of reviews the product has received rating: Customer rating for the product categories: Product categories or classifications asin: Unique identifier for each product seller_name: Name of the seller offering the product brand: Brand name of the product images_count: Number of images available for the product image_url: URL of the main product image url: Direct link to the product page delivery: Delivery-related information, such as estimated shipping time or cost features: List of product features or specifications And many more.

These are sample datasets and subsets derived from dozens of e-commerce datasets (public data) containing millions of records.

On-hot encoding for Categorical Attributes

In [42]:
# Reverse encoding of occupation and marital status
occupation_code = {0:'Unemployed', 1:'Official', 2:'Management'}
df['Occupation'] = df['Occupation'].map(occupation_code)
df['Marital Status'] = df['Marital Status'].map(lambda x: 'Married' if x==1 else 'Single')

encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False,handle_unknown="ignore")
# Fit and transform the dataframe
columns_to_encode = ['Category_Imputed','Occupation','Marital Status','genderImputed']
encoded_df = df.copy()
encoded_data = encoder.fit_transform(encoded_df[columns_to_encode])
encoded_df = pd.DataFrame(encoded_data, columns = encoder.get_feature_names_out(columns_to_encode),index=df.index)

# Concatenate the encoded DataFrame with the original DataFrame
df1 = pd.concat([df, encoded_df], axis=1)

# Drop the original columns that were encoded
df1 = df1.drop(columns_to_encode, axis=1)
df1.head(10)

Customer Segmentation using Machine Learning

K-means Clustering by Elbow method

In [45]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
# dict to store squared error for each iteration
results = {}

# k-means with increasing number of clusters
for i in range (1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(Scaled_df)
    results[i] = kmeans.inertia_

# plot the result
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(results.keys(), results.values(), marker='o', linestyle='--')
plt.plot([0.7, 3.2], [12000, 7000], color='#FF8400')
plt.plot([4.5, 9], [5700, 4000], color='#FF8400')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Sum of squared distance')
plt.show()

In the graph above, we can observe that the line drops sharply until cluster 4, indicating a rapid decrease in error as the number of clusters increases. After cluster 4, the decline in the line becomes more gradual. Therefore, we can conclude that our optimal number of clusters, also known as the elbow point, is 4. Meaning, 4 segments of customer

Text(0, 0.5, 'Percentage of Explained Variance Ratio')

In the graph above the first component covers about 12% of the total variance of the dataset. The second and third components capture 11% and 9% of the total variance of our dataset respectively. we see that the first 9 components together contain more than 90% of the total variance of our dataset. It is common practice in the industry to select a minimum number of components covering over 70% of the varieties. So we we’ll select the top 9 components to build our new k-means model.

# build k-means model with pca transformed components
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

kmeans_set = {"init": "random", "n_init": 10, "max_iter": 300, "random_state": 42}
Inertia = []
silhouette_coefficients = []
results = {}

for k in range (2, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans (n_clusters = k, **kmeans_set)
    kmeans.fit (df_pca)
    score = silhouette_score (df_pca, kmeans.labels_)
    silhouette_coefficients.append (score)
    results[i] = kmeans.inertia_
